results.lead_paragraph: The Atomic Energy Commission's $25,000 Fermi Award for 1972 is going to Dr. Manson Benedict of the Massachussetts Institute of Technology. The commission, noting that the award decision had been approved by President Nixon, said that Dr. Benedict was selected in recognition of his "leadership in the development of the nation's first gaseous diffusion plant that still produces fissionable uranium for weapons and power plant fuel" at Oak Ridge, Tenn.
